Ophir: Conjectures respecting the situation of Ophir are endless.
Grotius conjectures it to be a part of Arabia called Aphar by Arrian;
while Bochart and others have placed it in the island of Ceylon. Calmet
supposes it to have been situated in Armenia; but his late editor places
it at the head of the Indus. Josephus says that Ophir is the Indies,
called the Gold country; by which he is supposed to mean Chersonesus
Aurea, now Malacca, opposite Sumatra; and Lev. Poivre observes that the
inhabitants of these places call their gold mines ophirs.

